China Mobile, Hyundai Heavy, Neo: Asia Ex-Japan Equity Preview

-- B y   A n u c h i t   N g u y e n
-- 
2011-02-15T20:46:45Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-15/china-mobile-hyundai-heavy-neo-asia-ex-japan-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes in Asian trading, excluding Japan. Stock
symbols are in parentheses, and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.    China Mobile Ltd . (941 HK): The world’s biggest phone
carrier by market value said it’s seeking partners to bid for
network licenses overseas to share the risks of global expansion.
“China Mobile should be an international player,” Li Zhengmao,
a vice president at parent company China Mobile Communications
Corp., said in an interview at the Mobile World Congress in
Barcelona. The stock dropped 0.8 percent to HK$73.45.  Hyundai Heavy Industries Co. (009540 KS): The world’s
largest shipbuilder said its unit signed an agreement to build
six  container ships . The customer, which wasn’t identified, also
has the option to build four more vessels with Hyundai Samho
Heavy Industries Co., Hyundai Heavy said in a regulatory filing.
The shares climbed 2.1 percent to 454,000 won.  Lynas Corp. (LYC AU): Morgan Stanley increased its stake in
Lynas to 9.39 percent from 8.39 percent, the Sydney-based rare
earths miner said in a statement to the Australian stock
exchange. The shares added 0.5 percent to S$1.965.  Meritz Fire & Marine Insurance Co. (000060 KS): The
insurer’s financial strength rating may be downgraded by Moody’s
Investors Service, which cited the company’s plan to transfer
part of its assets to form a holding company. Meritz dropped 2.9
percent to 9,710 won.    Neo Solar Power Corp . (3576 TT): Neo Solar expects to boost
its annual solar cell production capacity to 1.3 gigawatts by
the end of this year, the Hsinchu, Taiwan-based company said in
an e-mailed statement. The solar cell maker targeted an annual
capacity of 1.2 gigawats by the end of 2011, Chairman Quincy Lin
told reporters in December. Neo Solar jumped 6.3 percent to
NT$78.80.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Anuchit Nguyen in Bangkok at 
